To properly format the given physics text into LaTeX, we will include the lens maker's formula, explain the sign convention, and derive the formula for the combined focal length of two lenses in contact. Here is the LaTeX code:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}

\begin{document}

\section*{Lens Maker's Formula and Combined Focal Length of Two Lenses}

The lens maker's formula relates the focal length \( f \) of a lens to the object distance \( u \) and the image distance \( v \). It is given by:

\begin{equation}
    \frac{1}{f} = \frac{1}{v} - \frac{1}{u}
\end{equation}

\subsection*{Sign Convention}

In the lens maker's formula, the following sign convention is used:
\begin{itemize}
    \item The object distance \( u \) is positive if the object is on the same side as the incoming light (real object).
    \item The image distance \( v \) is positive if the image is on the opposite side of the lens from the object (real image).
    \item The focal length \( f \) is positive for converging lenses and negative for diverging lenses.
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Combined Focal Length of Two Lenses in Contact}

When two lenses with focal lengths \( f_1 \) and \( f_2 \) are brought into contact, the focal length \( f \) of the combined lens system can be expressed as:

\begin{equation}
    \frac{1}{f} = \frac{1}{f_1} + \frac{1}{f_2}
\end{equation}

\subsection*{Derivation}

To derive this formula, consider the following:
\begin{itemize}
    \item Let the first lens form an image at a distance \( v_1 \) from the lens, given by the lens formula:
    \[
    \frac{1}{f_1} = \frac{1}{v_1} - \frac{1}{u}
    \]
    \item The image formed by the first lens acts as the object for the second lens. If the lenses are in contact, the object distance for the second lens is \( u_2 = -v_1 \).
    \item For the second lens, the lens formula is:
    \[
    \frac{1}{f_2} = \frac{1}{v} - \frac{1}{u_2}
    \]
    Substituting \( u_2 = -v_1 \), we have:
    \[
    \frac{1}{f_2} = \frac{1}{v} + \frac{1}{v_1}
    \]
    \item Adding the two equations:
    \[
    \frac{1}{f_1} + \frac{1}{f_2} = \left( \frac{1}{v_1} - \frac{1}{u} \right) + \left( \frac{1}{v} + \frac{1}{v_1} \right)
    \]
    \item Simplifying, we get:
    \[
    \frac{1}{f_1} + \frac{1}{f_2} = \frac{1}{v} - \frac{1}{u}
    \]
    \item Therefore, the combined focal length \( f \) is given by:
    \[
    \frac{1}{f} = \frac{1}{f_1} + \frac{1}{f_2}
    \]
\end{itemize}

\end{document}
```

This LaTeX code includes the lens maker's formula, explains the sign convention, and derives the formula for the combined focal length of two lenses in contact. Adjust the document class and packages as needed for your specific requirements.

