```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{graphicx}
\usepackage{amsmath}

\begin{document}

\section*{Problem}

A combination of two thin convex lenses are placed as in Fig. 15.9. An object is placed 5 cm in front of the first lens which has a focal length of 10 cm. The second lens is 10 cm behind the first lens and has a focal length of 12 cm.

\begin{enumerate}
    \item[(a)] Locate the image of the first lens with the aid of a ray diagram.
    \item[(b)] Is the image real or virtual? Erect or inverted?
    \item[(c)] Locate the final image for the lens combination.
    \item[(d)] Is the final image real or virtual? Erect or inverted?
\end{enumerate}

\begin{figure}[h]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.7\textwidth]{figure_15_9.png}
    \caption{Lens arrangement for the problem.}
    \label{fig:15_9}
\end{figure}

\section*{Solution}

\subsection*{(a) Image of the First Lens}

To locate the image formed by the first lens, we use the lens formula:

\[
\frac{1}{f_1} = \frac{1}{v_1} - \frac{1}{u_1}
\]

where \( f_1 = 10 \, \text{cm} \) is the focal length of the first lens, \( u_1 = -5 \, \text{cm} \) (object distance, taken as negative in lens convention), and \( v_1 \) is the image distance from the first lens.

Solving for \( v_1 \):

\[
\frac{1}{10} = \frac{1}{v_1} + \frac{1}{5}
\]

\[
\frac{1}{v_1} = \frac{1}{10} - \frac{1}{5} = \frac{1}{10} - \frac{2}{10} = -\frac{1}{10}
\]

\[
v_1 = -10 \, \text{cm}
\]

The image is formed 10 cm on the same side as the object, indicating a virtual image.

\subsection*{(b) Nature of the Image}

The image formed by the first lens is virtual and erect.

\subsection*{(c) Final Image for the Lens Combination}

The image formed by the first lens acts as a virtual object for the second lens. The object distance for the second lens \( u_2 \) is:

\[
u_2 = 10 \, \text{cm} - (-10 \, \text{cm}) = 20 \, \text{cm}
\]

Using the lens formula for the second lens:

\[
\frac{1}{f_2} = \frac{1}{v_2} - \frac{1}{u_2}
\]

where \( f_2 = 12 \, \text{cm} \).

\[
\frac{1}{12} = \frac{1}{v_2} - \frac{1}{20}
\]

\[
\frac{1}{v_2} = \frac{1}{12} + \frac{1}{20} = \frac{5}{60} + \frac{3}{60} = \frac{8}{60} = \frac{2}{15}
\]

\[
v_2 = 7.5 \, \text{cm}
\]

The final image is located 7.5 cm behind the second lens.

\subsection*{(d) Nature of the Final Image}

The final image is real and inverted.

\end{document}
```

