\begin{document}

\section*{Problem}

(a) Obtain the expression for $\Delta \theta$, the half-width at half-maximum of the central maximum of single-slit Fraunhofer diffraction.

(b) Calculate $\Delta \theta$ for $\lambda = 4\,\text{nm}$. [Osmania University]

\section*{Solution}

\subsection*{(a) Expression for $\Delta \theta$}

In single-slit Fraunhofer diffraction, the angular width of the central maximum can be determined using the condition for the first minimum, which occurs at an angle $\theta$ given by:

\[
a \sin \theta = m \lambda
\]

where $a$ is the slit width, $\lambda$ is the wavelength of the light, and $m$ is the order of the minimum. For the first minimum, $m = 1$, so:

\[
a \sin \theta = \lambda
\]

The half-width at half-maximum $\Delta \theta$ is approximately given by the angle between the central maximum and the first minimum:

\[
\Delta \theta \approx \frac{\lambda}{a}
\]

\subsection*{(b) Calculation of $\Delta \theta$ for $\lambda = 4\,\text{nm}$}

Assuming a slit width $a$, the half-width at half-maximum is:

\[
\Delta \theta \approx \frac{4\,\text{nm}}{a}
\]

To calculate $\Delta \theta$, the value of $a$ must be known. If $a$ is provided, substitute it into the expression to find $\Delta \theta$.

\end{document}
```

