To solve this problem, we need to calculate the resolving power of the prism and then determine the length of the base required to resolve the sodium lines. Here is the LaTeX code that formats the solution:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{siunitx}

\begin{document}

\title{Resolving Power of a Prism}
\author{Vikram University}
\date{}
\maketitle

\section*{Problem Statement}

The refractive indices of a glass prism for the C and F lines are 1.6545 and 1.6635, respectively. The wavelengths of these two lines in the solar spectrum are \SI{6563}{\angstrom} and \SI{5270}{\angstrom}, respectively. Calculate the length of the base of a \SI{60}{\degree} prism which is capable of resolving sodium lines of wavelengths \SI{5890}{\angstrom} and \SI{5896}{\angstrom}.

\section*{Solution}

The resolving power \( R \) of a prism is given by:
\[
R = \frac{\Delta \lambda}{\lambda} = \frac{d n}{d \lambda} \cdot L
\]
where \( \Delta \lambda = \lambda_2 - \lambda_1 \) is the difference in wavelengths of the sodium lines, \( \lambda \) is the average wavelength, \( \frac{d n}{d \lambda} \) is the dispersion of the prism, and \( L \) is the base length of the prism.

Given:
\begin{align*}
n_C &= 1.6545, \\
n_F &= 1.6635, \\
\lambda_C &= \SI{6563}{\angstrom}, \\
\lambda_F &= \SI{5270}{\angstrom}, \\
\lambda_1 &= \SI{5890}{\angstrom}, \\
\lambda_2 &= \SI{5896}{\angstrom}.
\end{align*}

First, calculate the dispersion \( \frac{d n}{d \lambda} \):
\[
\frac{d n}{d \lambda} = \frac{n_F - n_C}{\lambda_F - \lambda_C} = \frac{1.6635 - 1.6545}{5270 - 6563} = \frac{0.0090}{-1293} \approx -6.96 \times 10^{-6} \, \text{\angstrom}^{-1}
\]

Calculate \( \Delta \lambda \) and \( \lambda \):
\[
\Delta \lambda = \lambda_2 - \lambda_1 = 5896 - 5890 = \SI{6}{\angstrom}
\]
\[
\lambda = \frac{\lambda_1 + \lambda_2}{2} = \frac{5890 + 5896}{2} = \SI{5893}{\angstrom}
\]

Now, calculate the resolving power \( R \):
\[
R = \frac{\Delta \lambda}{\lambda} = \frac{6}{5893} \approx 0.001018
\]

Finally, solve for the base length \( L \):
\[
L = \frac{R}{\left| \frac{d n}{d \lambda} \right|} = \frac{0.001018}{6.96 \times 10^{-6}} \approx 146.26 \, \text{cm}
\]

Thus, the length of the base of the prism required to resolve the sodium lines is approximately \SI{146.26}{\centi\meter}.

\end{document}
```

