\section*{Problem}

A tube 20 cm long containing sugar solution rotates the plane of polarization through an angle of $13.2^\circ$. If the specific rotation is $66^\circ$, find the amount of sugar present in a litre of the solution. [Osmania University 2003]

\section*{Solution}

The specific rotation $\alpha$ is given by the formula:

\[
\alpha = \frac{\theta}{l \cdot c}
\]

where:
\begin{itemize}
    \item $\theta = 13.2^\circ$ is the observed angle of rotation,
    \item $l = 20 \, \text{cm} = 0.2 \, \text{dm}$ is the length of the tube (converted to decimeters),
    \item $c$ is the concentration of the sugar solution in grams per deciliter (g/dL).
\end{itemize}

Given that the specific rotation $\alpha$ is $66^\circ$, we can rearrange the formula to solve for $c$:

\[
c = \frac{\theta}{\alpha \cdot l}
\]

Substituting the given values:

\[
c = \frac{13.2^\circ}{66^\circ \times 0.2 \, \text{dm}}
\]

\[
c = \frac{13.2}{13.2} = 1 \, \text{g/dL}
\]

Since the solution is 1 g/dL, the amount of sugar in a litre (10 dL) of the solution is:

\[
\text{Amount of sugar} = 1 \, \text{g/dL} \times 10 \, \text{dL} = 10 \, \text{g}
\]

Therefore, the amount of sugar present in a litre of the solution is \textbf{10 grams}.

\end{document}
```

